==English==

===Etymology===
From the American sport of [[baseball]]; the [[hardball]] is the heavier and harder type of the two types of throwing ball used when playing that sport (i.e. {{m|en|softball}}).

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en|En-au-play hardball.ogg|Audio (AU)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|*}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To use every means possible to achieve a goal, especially in disregarding the harm caused.
#: {{ux|en|He was more than willing to extend the terms of the loan, but his boss decided to '''play hardball''' and demanded a balloon payment.}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To act rough and ruthless, especially in politics or business.
#: {{ux|en|So you wanna '''play hardball'''?}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2021 October 6|author=Christian Wolmar|title=Both sides must work together to get London back on track|journal=RAIL|issue=941|page=35|text=But if ministers keep on '''playing hardball''' with TfL because of narrow party interests, London will lose out. Forcing a 4.8% rise on London fares will only encourage congestion at a time when the roads are already full  and public transport is underused.}}

